<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870804-0103 </DOCNO><HL> REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:Sanctimonious Sanctions</HL><DD> 08/04/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> AFRICMONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON) </IN><TEXT>   For years Zimbabwe's leaders have demanded that the U.S. and other Western nations impose sanctions on South Africa. Zimbabwe has extensive trade of its own with South Africa, but it has long promised to impose a trade ban once others took the sanctions lead. Then last week, Zimbabwe's cabinet rejected curbs on trade with South Africa after hearing evidence that Zimbabwe couldn't afford them. In other words, it is somehow acceptable if sanctions cost black South Africans their jobs but the moral imperative of sanctions ends when the pain hits closer to home. </TEXT></DOC>